{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519394"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:10:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13007"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13007"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.19,0.46,0.14,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5444"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25732"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1780"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44294"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 41-year-old woman presents to her primary care physician with a three month history of fatigue and weight loss. She denies any fever, night sweats, or chills. She does not smoke and drinks several glasses of wine at weekends. She is not on any medications. On examination her blood pressure is 115/72 mmHg, pulse 84/min and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. She appears pale and there are palpable and non-tender cervical and axillary lymph nodes. Abdominal examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA complete blood count shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 100 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 35.0 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 80 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA peripheral blood smear shows lymphocytosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia","Hodgkin\u2019s lymphoma","Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia","Non-Hodgkin\u2019s lymphoma","Granulocytic leukaemia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of fatigue and weight loss is nonspecific but can be attributed to anaemia and cachexia, which is commonly observed in lymphoid malignancies. With palpable cervical and axillary lymphadenopathy, and lymphocytosis seen on peripheral blood smear, the most likely diagnosis for this patient\u2019s presentation would be \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL).\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute lymphoblastic leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E would present with lymphoblasts on peripheral blood smear, accompanied by higher levels of lactate dehydrogenase, in contrast to the lymphocytosis seen in CLL.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHodgkin\u2019s lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E would present with Reed-Sternberg cells on lymph node biopsy, clasically with a mediastinal mass, but this presentation would not usually include lymphocytosis or thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-Hodgkin\u2019s lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E would present with lymphadenopathy and biopsy showing malignant lymphoid cells, but the peripheral blood smear result of lymphocytosis suggests CLL over non-Hodgkin\u2019s lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulocytic leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E would present with a predominance of myeloid blasts and symptoms related to the high white blood cell count, such as fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic lymphocytic leukaemia is a B-cell malignancy, associated with age with a good responsiveness to chemotherapy or targetted therapies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, CLL is the most likely diagnosis for this patient\u2019s presentation due to the finding of lymphocytosis on the peripheral blood smear, with palpable peripheral lymph nodes, and presenting symptoms of fatigue, weight loss, thrombocytopenia, and mild anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic lymphocytic leukemia presents with lymphocytosis on peripheral blood smear, palpable lymph nodes, and symptoms such as fatigue, weight loss, thrombocytopenia, and mild anaemia."],"references":["Shanafelt TD, Wang XV, Kay NE, Hanson CA, O\u0027Brien SM, Barrientos JC, et al. Ibrutinib-Rituximab or Chemoimmunotherapy for Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia. N Engl J Med. 2019;381(5):432-43. doi: 10.1056/NEJMoa1817073. PMID: 31166679."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25732"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13007"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25732"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-12-28T09:34:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-12-28T09:34:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5444"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud8